----------------------------------¶

1 Presentation of the problem and the dataset¶

The goal of the project is to develop our own information retrieval system on a specific corpus. In order to do that, we are allowed to use any kind of pre-treatment and manipulate the vocabulary of the documents.

The dataset is a medical corpus. The document are abstracts of medical publication from PubMed and the queries are scraps of vulgarisation on the topics linked to some PubMed articles. It’s a very complex corpus where modern deep learning approaches fail to perform better than BM25.

1.1 - Presentation of the dataset¶

def load_doc(filename,dic=defaultdict(dict),reqdoc=False):
	with open(filename) as file:
		lines = file.readlines()
	for line in lines:
		tabLine = line.split('\t')
		if reqdoc:
			req = tabLine[0]
			doc = tabLine[2]
			dic[req][doc]=int(tabLine[3])
		else:
			key = tabLine[0]
			value = tabLine[1]
			dic[key] = value
	return dic

def loadNFCorpus():
	dicDoc    = load_doc("./project1-2023/dev.docs",{})
	dicReq    = load_doc("./project1-2023/dev.all.queries",{})
	dicReqDoc = load_doc("./project1-2023/dev.2-1-0.qrel",defaultdict(dict),True)
	return dicDoc,dicReq,dicReqDoc

why deep fried foods may cause cancer in the latest study on dietary patterns and breast cancer risk among women , healthier eating was associated with eliminating three-quarters of the odds of breast cancer , whereas less healthy eating was associated with up to nearly eight times the odds . included in the unhealthy eating pattern was the consumption of deep-fried foods , which have previously been linked to breast cancer , pancreatic cancer , lung cancer , oral and throat cancers , esophageal cancer , and cancer of the voicebox . no deep fried foods ? what ’ s a southern belle to do ? instead of deep fried foods , how about the traditional southern diet , characterized by high intakes of cooked greens , beans , legumes , cabbage , sweet potatoes and cornbread , which may reduce the risk of invasive breast cancer significantly . what about the consumption of deep-fried foods and risk of prostate cancer ? researchers at the fred hutchinson cancer research center and the university of washington found that eating french fries , fried chicken , fried fish , and doughnuts was associated with about a third greater odds of prostate cancer . after stratifying for tumor aggressiveness , they found slightly stronger associations with more aggressive disease , suggesting that regular intake of deep-fried foods may contribute to the progression of prostate cancer as well . what in deep fried foods is so bad for us ? just heating oil that hot can generate potentially carcinogenic compounds , and then known carcinogens such as heterocyclic amines and polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons form when the muscles of chickens and fish are cooked at that temperature . deep-fried plants , on the other hand , can form acrylamide . i did a video about acrylamide back in 2008 , suggesting it ’ s a probable human carcinogen ( see acrylamide in french fries ) . since then , studies have suggested pregnant women may want to cut back on french fries to protect the growth of their baby ’ s body and brain . based on a study ( highlighted in my video , cancer risk from french fries ) feeding people a little bag of potato chips every day for a month , it now seems acrylamide may also cause inflammation as well , which could explain its purported role in cancer progression . acrylamide intake has been associated with endometrial cancer , ovarian cancer , lung cancer , kidney cancer , and esophageal cancer . how much cancer risk are we talking about ? taiwanese researchers examined lifetime cancer risk and french fry consumption . the researchers picked on french fries because they comprise by far the greatest percentage contribution of acrylamide to the diets of children . they estimated that , at most , one or two boys and girls out of every ten thousand would develop cancer eating french fries that they would otherwise not have developed if they hadn ’ t eaten french fries . so it ’ s not as bad as eating something like fried fish , or fried chicken , but how much is that saying ? the level of cancer risk in both boys and girls associated with french fries depends on how long and hot they ’ re fried . in europe , the food industry swore that they ’ d self-regulate and control fry times to decrease acrylamide levels , but we ’ ve yet to see any subsequent change in acrylamide levels in french fries . researchers continue to urge that the cooking temperature should be as low as possible and the cooking time should be as short as possible , “ while still maintaining a tasty quality ” of course . we wouldn ’ t want to reduce cancer risk too much — they might not taste as good ! blanching the potatoes first reduces acrylamide formation , but potato chip companies complain that , not only would it muck with the flavor , but it would These dictionaries contain information about the documents, queries, and their associations:

  • dicDoc:

This dictionary contains information about medical documents. Each key represents a document ID (e.g., 'MED-118', 'MED-329'). The corresponding values are the text content of the documents.

  • dicReq:

This dictionary appears to contains simplifications of previous articles. Each key represents a query ID (e.g., 'PLAIN-901', 'PLAIN-912').

  • dicReqDoc (defaultdict of dictionaries):

This dictionnary corresponds to associations between several Medicine documents and one simplification. The numerical value may indicate some form of relevance or weight.(e.g., {'PLAIN-901' : {'MED-2421 ':2 ... }...)

2 Explaination of the raw algorithm¶

We created definitions to explain the code given in the project

We've broken down the example code into several functions to make it easier to understand.

The run_bm25_only method returns a score to evaluate the information retrieval between a request and many scientific articles. Inside :

  • loadNFCorpus : loads the data in three different dictionaries
  • selectNb : Select a number of request to reduce the amount of data
  • getAllVocab : Return for each document two list of all the vocabulary present in the documents and in the requests
  • getTokenDoc : Return each documents to a token
  • getTokenReq : Same for requests
  • bm25_ngcd : Initiate a bm25 model using bm25 Okapi and the list of documents. Then calculate a list of score for each request. The score should be high if the documents correspond to the request. Finally ndcg score evaluate the quality of the results. Here is an example:
    • bm25score = [0.9 , 0.01 , 0.8, 0,2...]
    • trueDoc = [ 1. , 0 , 1 , 0 ...]
    • => here the ndcg score should by high beacause high probabilities are associated to true documents (1) and low to documents that doesn't correspond to the request (0)

def text2TokenList(text,l=[]):
  stopword = stopwords.words('english')
  word_tokens = word_tokenize(text.lower())
  word_tokens_without_stops = [word for word in word_tokens if word not in stopword and len(word)>2]
  return word_tokens_without_stops

def selectNb(dictRD,start,end):
  doc, docReq = [], defaultdict(dict)
  i = start
  for r in dictRD:
    if i > (end - i) :
      break
    for d in dictRD[r]:
      docReq[r][d] = dictRD[r][d]
      doc.append(d)
      i = i + 1
  req = list(docReq.keys())
  doc = list(set(doc))
  return docReq, doc, req

def getAllVocab(document,ids):
  vocab = {}
  for id in ids:
    words = text2TokenList(document[id])
    for w in words:
      if w not in vocab:
        vocab[w] = w
  return list(vocab)

def getTokenDoc(ids,documents):
  tokenList, tokenId, tokenId_NB   = [], [], {}
  i = 0
  for id in ids:
    token = text2TokenList(documents[id])
    tokenList.append(token)
    tokenId.append(id)
    tokenId_NB[id] = i
    i = i + 1
  return tokenList, tokenId,tokenId_NB

def getTokenReq(ids,documents):
  tokenList,tokenId, tokenId_NB = {}, [], {}
  i = 0
  for id in ids:
    token = text2TokenList(documents[id])
    tokenList[id] = token
    tokenId.append(id)
    tokenId_NB[id] = i
    i = i + 1
  return tokenList,tokenId, tokenId_NB

def getTrueDocs(len_,req,corpusDicoDocName,dicReqDocToKeep):
  true = np.zeros(len_)
  for docId in corpusDicoDocName:
    if req in dicReqDocToKeep:
      if docId in dicReqDocToKeep[req]:
        pos       = corpusDicoDocName[docId]
        true[pos] = dicReqDocToKeep[req][docId]
  return true

def bm25_ngcd(ndcgTop, reqTokens,reqDocs, docTokens, docIndices):
  bm25 = BM25Okapi(docTokens)
  ndcg, nbReq = 0, 0

  for r in reqTokens:
    doc_scores = bm25.get_scores(reqTokens[r])
    trueDocs   = getTrueDocs(len(docTokens),r,docIndices,reqDocs)
    ndcg       = ndcg + ndcg_score([trueDocs], [doc_scores],k=ndcgTop)
    nbReq      = nbReq + 1
  return ndcg / nbReq


def ndgcScore_bm25(startDoc,endDoc,ndcgTop=5):
  allDoc, allReq, allReqDoc = loadNFCorpus()
  #_____________SELECT INFO___________________
  reqDocs, docs, reqs = selectNb(allReqDoc,startDoc,endDoc)
  #____________ALL VOCAB DOC & REQ_____________
  allVocabListDoc = getAllVocab(allDoc,docs)
  allVocabListReq = getAllVocab(allReq,reqs)
  #_____________TOKENISE DOC & REQ______________
  docTokens, docNames , docIndices = getTokenDoc(docs,allDoc)
  reqTokens, reqNames , reqIndices = getTokenReq(reqs,allReq)
  #_______________EVALUATE SCORE________________
  mean_ndcgBM25 = bm25_ngcd(ndcgTop, reqTokens,reqDocs, docTokens, docIndices)
  return mean_ndcgBM25

def tokenizeDoc(text,delWords=[],lem=False,link=True):
  stopword = stopwords.words('english')
  token = word_tokenize(text.lower())
  token = [word for word in token if word not in stopword and len(word)>2]
  if link:
    token = [word for word in token if not any(char in word for char in [".", "-", "/","\\n","@","html","<",">"])] #delete link and adresse
  if lem:
    lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
    token = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word) for word in token]
  if len(delWords)>0:
    token = [word for word in token if word not in delWords]
  return token

def AllVocab(document,lem=False,link=True):
  vocab = {}
  for id in document:
    words = tokenizeDoc(document[id],lem=lem,link=link)
    for w in words:
      if w not in vocab:
        vocab[w] = 1
      else:
        vocab[w] = vocab[w]+1
  return vocab

def showAllVocab(sorted_dic,a=0,b=50):
  keys   = list(sorted_dic.keys())
  values = list(sorted_dic.values())
  freq   = np.round(values/np.sum(values)*100,3)
  print(f"Nombre de mots            : {np.sum(values)}")
  print(f"Nombre de mots différents : {len(keys)}\n")
  fig = go.Figure()
  fig.add_trace(go.Bar(x=keys[a:b],y=freq[a:b], marker=dict(color=freq[a:b], colorscale='Viridis', showscale=True)))
  fig.update_xaxes(tickangle=45)
  fig.update_layout(
      title=f"Frequence des mots entre {a} et {b} en %",
      xaxis_title='Catégories',
      yaxis_title='Valeurs',)
  fig.show()
  print(f"Ces {b-a} mots representent {np.round(np.sum(values[a:b])*100/np.sum(values))}% du nombre de mots dans les documents et seulement {np.round((b-a)*100/len(keys),2)}% des mots différents")

def delWords(document,n=15,lem=False):
  vocab = AllVocab(dicDoc,lem)
  vocab = dict(sorted(vocab.items(), key=lambda item: item[1],reverse=True))
  return list(vocab.keys())[:n]

#TFIDF
def allWords(documents,delWords=[],lem=False,link=True):
  words = []
  for doc in documents:
    words.extend(tokenizeDoc(doc,delWords=delWords,lem=lem,link=link))
  return words

def tfidfVector(document,delWords=[],lem=False,link=True):
  all_words = allWords(document,delWords=delWords,lem=lem,link=link)
  tfidf_vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer()
  tfidf_matrix = tfidf_vectorizer.fit_transform(all_words)
  tfidf_embeddings = tfidf_matrix.toarray()
  return tfidf_embeddings

#word2Vector
def word2Vector(document, delWords=[], lem=False, link=True):
    all_words = allWords(document, delWords, lem)
    model = Word2Vec(sentences=[all_words], vector_size=100, window=5, min_count=1, sg=0)
    vectors = model.wv
    model.wv.save_word2vec_format("word2vec.model")
    word2vec_array = np.array([vectors[word] for word in all_words if word in vectors.index_to_key])
    return word2vec_array, model

#fastText
def fastText(document,delWords=[],lem=False,link=True):
    all_words = allWords(document,delWords,lem,link)
    fasttext_model = FastText(sentences=[all_words], vector_size=100, window=5, min_count=1, workers=4, epochs=20)
    fasttext_emb = np.array([fasttext_model.wv[word] for word in all_words])
    return fasttext_emb

#Visualize with TSNE
def tsneViz(embeddings, method, perplexity=30, allWords=None, num_clusters=5):
    tsne = TSNE(n_components=3, random_state=42, perplexity=perplexity)
    embeddings_tsne = tsne.fit_transform(embeddings)
    # Apply K-Means clustering
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=num_clusters, random_state=42)
    clusters = kmeans.fit_predict(embeddings)
    # Create a DataFrame for Plotly
    df = pd.DataFrame(embeddings_tsne, columns=['Dim1', 'Dim2', 'Dim3'])
    df['Word'] = allWords
    df['Cluster'] = clusters.astype(str)  # Convert cluster labels to string for categorical coloring
    fig = px.scatter_3d(df, x='Dim1', y='Dim2', z='Dim3', text='Word',
                        color='Cluster', title=f"{method} Embeddings - 3D t-SNE Visualization with Clusters",
                        hover_name='Word', hover_data={'Word': True, 'Cluster': True})
    fig.update_traces(marker=dict(size=5))
    fig.show()

The principle of t-SNE (t-distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding) is a dimension reduction technique used in data analysis. A key parameter, called "perplexity," is used to balance the observation of the overall and local structure of the data during reduction. Perplexity measures the extent to which the probability distribution in the reduced dimension reflects that of the original dimension. Low perplexity focuses on the local details of the data, while high perplexity promotes a more global representation to maintain the structure of the original dataset, thereby offering a better overall representation of the data.

#fast text
def train_fasttext_model(corpus, model_path, dim=100, epoch=5):
    model = FastText(sentences=corpus, vector_size=dim, epochs=epoch)
    model.save(model_path)
    return model

def fasttext_embedding(tokens, model):
    embeddings = [model.wv[token] for token in tokens if token in model.wv]
    return np.mean(embeddings, axis=0) if embeddings else np.zeros(model.vector_size)

def fastTextDoc(document, delWords=[], lem=False, link=True):
    doc  = [tokenizeDoc(doc,delWords=delWords,lem=lem,link=link) for doc in document]
    embeddings_list = []
    model = train_fasttext_model(doc, 'fasttext_model.model')
    for doc_tokens in doc:
      req_embedding = fasttext_embedding(doc_tokens, model)
      embeddings_list.append(req_embedding)
    return np.array(embeddings_list), model

#sbert
def sbertDoc(document, model):
    doc = [tokenizeDoc(doc, delWords=[], lem=True, link=True) for doc in document]
    embeddings_list = []
    for doc_tokens in doc:
        req_embedding = model.encode(" ".join(doc_tokens))
        embeddings_list.append(req_embedding)
    return np.array(embeddings_list), model

#Visualize with TSNE
def tsneVizDoc(embeddings, method, perplexity=30, requestNames=None):
    tsne = TSNE(n_components=3, random_state=42, perplexity=perplexity)
    embeddings_tsne = tsne.fit_transform(embeddings)
    df = pd.DataFrame(embeddings_tsne, columns=['Dim1', 'Dim2', 'Dim3'])
    df['Request name'] = requestNames
    fig = px.scatter_3d(df, x='Dim1', y='Dim2', z='Dim3', color='Request name',
                    title=f"{method} Embeddings - 3D t-SNE Visualization with Clusters")
    fig.update_traces(marker=dict(size=5))
    fig.show()

#load documents
def load_doc(filename,dic=defaultdict(dict),reqdoc=False):
	with open(filename) as file:
		lines = file.readlines()
	for line in lines:
		tabLine = line.split('\t')
		if reqdoc:
			req = tabLine[0]
			doc = tabLine[2]
			dic[req][doc]=int(tabLine[3])
		else:
			key = tabLine[0]
			value = tabLine[1]
			dic[key] = value
	return dic

def loadNFCorpus():
	dicDoc    = load_doc("./project1-2023/dev.docs",{})
	dicReq    = load_doc("./project1-2023/dev.all.queries",{})
	dicReqDoc = load_doc("./project1-2023/dev.2-1-0.qrel",defaultdict(dict),True)
	return dicDoc,dicReq,dicReqDoc

def selectNb(dictRD,start,end):
  doc, docReq = [], defaultdict(dict)
  i = start
  for r in dictRD:
    if i > (end - i) :
      break
    for d in dictRD[r]:
      docReq[r][d] = dictRD[r][d]
      doc.append(d)
      i = i + 1
  req = list(docReq.keys())
  doc = list(set(doc))
  return docReq, doc, req

#text pre-processing & tokenization
def tokenizeDoc2(text,delWords=[],lem=False,link=True):
  stopword = stopwords.words('english')
  word_tokens = word_tokenize(text.lower())
  word_tokens_without_stops = [word for word in word_tokens if word not in stopword and len(word)>2]
  return word_tokens_without_stops

def tokenizeDoc(text,delWords=[],lem=False,link=True):
  stopword = stopwords.words('english')
  token = word_tokenize(text.lower())
  token = [word for word in token if word not in stopword and len(word)>2]
  if link:
    token = [word for word in token if not any(char in word for char in [".", "-", "/","\\n","@","html","<",">"])]
  if lem:
    lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
    token = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word) for word in token]
  if len(delWords)>0:
    token = [word for word in token if word not in delWords]
  return token

def getTokenDoc(ids,documents,delWords=[],lem=False,link=True):
  tokenList, tokenId, tokenId_NB   = [], [], {}
  i = 0
  for id in ids:
    token = tokenizeDoc(documents[id],delWords=delWords,lem=lem,link=link)
    tokenList.append(token)
    tokenId.append(id)
    tokenId_NB[id] = i
    i = i + 1
  return tokenList, tokenId,tokenId_NB

def getTokenReq(ids,documents,delWords=[],lem=False,link=True):
  tokenList,tokenId, tokenId_NB = {}, [], {}
  i = 0
  for id in ids:
    token = tokenizeDoc(documents[id],delWords=delWords,lem=lem,link=link)
    tokenList[id] = token
    tokenId.append(id)
    tokenId_NB[id] = i
    i = i + 1
  return tokenList,tokenId, tokenId_NB

# FAST TEXT
def trainFastText(corpus, model_path, dim=100, epoch=5):
    model = FastText(sentences=corpus, vector_size=dim, epochs=epoch)
    model.save(model_path)
    return model

def fasttextembedding(tokens, model):
    embeddings = [model.wv[token] for token in tokens if token in model.wv]
    return np.mean(embeddings, axis=0) if embeddings else np.zeros(model.vector_size)

def ngcdScore_fastext(ndcgTop, reqTokens, reqDocs, docTokens, docIndices, model):
    ndgc, nbReq = 0, 0
    for r in reqTokens:
      req_embedding = fasttextembedding(reqTokens[r], model)
      doc_scores = [cosine_similarity(req_embedding, fasttextembedding(doc, model)) for doc in docTokens]
      trueDocs = getTrueDocs(len(docTokens), r, docIndices, reqDocs)
      ndgc += ndcg_score([trueDocs], [doc_scores], k=ndcgTop)
      nbReq += 1
    return ndgc / nbReq

#SBERT
def sbert_embedding(sentences, model):
    embeddings = model.encode(sentences)
    return embeddings

def sbertDoc(document, model):
    embeddings_list = []
    for doc_tokens in document:
        req_embedding = sbert_embedding([" ".join(doc_tokens)], model)
        embeddings_list.append(np.squeeze(req_embedding))
    return np.array(embeddings_list)

def ngcdScore_sbert(ndcgTop, reqTokens, reqDocs, sbertEmbeddingDoc, docIndices,model):
    ndgc, nbReq = 0, 0
    for r in reqTokens:
        req_embedding = sbert_embedding([" ".join(reqTokens[r])], model)
        doc_scores = [cosine_similarity(req_embedding[0], doc) for doc in sbertEmbeddingDoc]
        trueDocs = getTrueDocs(len(sbertEmbeddingDoc), r, docIndices, reqDocs)
        ndgc += ndcg_score([trueDocs], [doc_scores], k=ndcgTop)
        nbReq += 1
    return ndgc / nbReq

def cosine_similarity(vec1, vec2):
    norm_vec1 = np.linalg.norm(vec1)
    norm_vec2 = np.linalg.norm(vec2)
    if norm_vec1 == 0 or norm_vec2 == 0:
        return 0.0
    return np.dot(vec1, vec2) / (norm_vec1 * norm_vec2)

def getTrueDocs(len_,req,corpusDicoDocName,dicReqDocToKeep):
  true = np.zeros(len_)
  for docId in corpusDicoDocName:
    if req in dicReqDocToKeep:
      if docId in dicReqDocToKeep[req]:
        pos       = corpusDicoDocName[docId]
        true[pos] = dicReqDocToKeep[req][docId]
  return true

def AllVocab(document,lem=False,link=True):
  vocab = {}
  for id in document:
    words = tokenizeDoc(document[id],lem=lem,link=link)
    for w in words:
      if w not in vocab:
        vocab[w] = 1
      else:
        vocab[w] = vocab[w]+1
  return vocab

def delWords(document,n=15,lem=False):
  vocab = AllVocab(dicDoc,lem)
  vocab = dict(sorted(vocab.items(), key=lambda item: item[1],reverse=True))
  return list(vocab.keys())[:n]
In [ ]:
def evaluateSimilarity(startDoc, endDoc, ndcgTop=5,method="sbert",delWordsDoc=[],delWordsReq=[],lem=False,link=True):
    #_____________SELECT INFO___________________
    allDoc, allReq, allReqDoc = loadNFCorpus()
    reqDocs, docs, reqs = selectNb(allReqDoc, startDoc, endDoc)
    #_____________TOKENIZE DOC & REQ______________
    docTokens, docNames, docIndices = getTokenDoc(docs, allDoc,delWords=delWordsDoc,lem=lem,link=link) #
    reqTokens, reqNames, reqIndices = getTokenReq(reqs, allReq,delWords=delWordsReq,lem=lem,link=link)
    #_____________SIMILARITY SCORE___________
    if method == "fasttext":
      corpus = [docTokens[doc_idx] for doc_idx in docIndices.values()] + list(reqTokens.values()) #create corpus to train model
      model = trainFastText(corpus, 'fasttext_model.model')                                       # train model
      mean_ndcg = ngcdScore_fastext(ndcgTop, reqTokens, reqDocs, docTokens, docIndices, model)    #get embeddings, cos sim and get ndgc score
    if method == "sbert":
      model = SentenceTransformer('paraphrase-MiniLM-L6-v2')       #call pre-trained model
      sbertEmbeddingDoc = sbertDoc(docTokens, model)               #get embeddings
      mean_ndcg = ngcdScore_sbert(ndcgTop, reqTokens, reqDocs, sbertEmbeddingDoc, docIndices,model)  #get cos sim and ndgc score
    return mean_ndcg
